                            <div class="hover-line" ">The Science Behind Cookies: Why Baking Is a Delicious Chemistry Experiment</div>
                        </span>
                        
                    </div>
                    <div class="content">
                        <p><span  class="letter">I</span>ngredients: A Chemical Toolbox
                            Each ingredient in a cookie recipe has a specific role, and together, they interact in complex ways.
                        <br>Flour: The base of most cookies, flour contains proteins that form gluten when mixed with liquid. Gluten gives cookies structure and texture.
                        <br>Sugar: Not only adds sweetness but affects how cookies spread and brown. Sugar caramelizes at high temperatures, giving cookies a golden color and rich flavor.
                        <br>Fat (Butter/Oil): Fat adds richness and tenderness. It also affects how much cookies spread during baking. Melted butter, for example, leads to flatter, chewier cookies, while solid butter can make them puffier.
                        <br>Eggs: Eggs act as binders and help with structure. The proteins in eggs firm up as they bake, holding everything together.
                        <br>Leavening Agents (Baking Soda/Powder): These produce carbon dioxide bubbles that cause cookies to rise and become light.
                        <br>Salt: Enhances flavor and balances sweetness.
                        <br>Even small changes in the ratio of these ingredients can lead to big differences in the final product.
                            Heat: The Kitchen Lab
                            When you place cookie dough into the oven, you start a chain of physical and chemical transformations:
                            <br><b>1-Melting:</b> Butter melts first, causing the dough to spread.
                            <br><b>2-Evaporation:</b>  Water in the dough turns into steam, helping to puff up the cookie.
                            <br><b>3-Maillard Reaction:</b>  Around 300°F (150°C), proteins and sugars begin to react, creating hundreds of flavor compounds and giving cookies their brown, toasty color.
                            <br><b>4-Caramelization:</b>Sugar begins to break down into new compounds, adding depth to the flavor and a slight crunch to the edges.
                            <br><b>5-Protein Coagulation & Starch Gelatinization:</b> Eggs and flour firm up to create the cookie’s final texture.
                            <br>All these processes combine to create the crispy edges, chewy centers, or soft textures that cookie lovers crave.
                            Cookies are more than comfort food — they’re edible chemistry. From protein structure to sugar reactions, every bite reflects fascinating scientific principles. Understanding the science of cookies helps bakers control results and become more creative in the kitchen.
                            So next time you bake a batch, remember: you're not just making dessert — you’re conducting an experiment that ends in delicious results!
                        </p>
