                        <div class="content" >
                            <p>
                                <span class="letter">C</span>oronavirus, also known as COVID-19, is a virus that caused a global pandemic starting in late 2019. It belongs to a family of viruses called coronaviruses, which can infect both animals and humans. The virus spreads mainly through droplets when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or talks.<br> How It Works
                                Coronavirus infects the human body by attaching to cells in the lungs and throat using a special “spike” protein. Once inside the cells, it hijacks them to make more copies of itself. This can lead to symptoms like fever, cough, and fatigue — and in severe cases, difficulty breathing.<br>
                                Why It Spread Quickly
                                COVID-19 spreads easily because people can carry the virus without symptoms. This made it hard to detect and control early. Air travel and large gatherings helped it move between countries quickly.
                                <br> Vaccines and Immunity
                                Scientists developed vaccines in record time using mRNA technology (like Pfizer and Moderna). These vaccines teach the body to recognize the spike protein and build immunity. Getting vaccinated helps prevent severe illness and reduce the spread.<br>
                                Scientific Response
                                The pandemic led to huge progress in:
                                Virus tracking (genome sequencing)
                                Vaccine research
                                Public health systems
                                It also reminded the world how important science, global cooperation, and healthcare are in facing future pandemics.<br>
                                Coronavirus was a major challenge, but science played a key role in understanding, fighting, and managing the outbreak. Research continues today to improve treatments, study long-term effects, and prepare for future threats.
                            </p>
